# Mechanical Installation Procedure — Packaging Line

## Objective
Document the process of installing and aligning stationary mechanical
equipment on a multi-station packaging line, starting from blueprint
interpretation through to commissioning-ready alignment.

## 1. Blueprint reading approach
- Identify station layout drawing: equipment footprint, orientation, and
  clearances between stations
- Cross-reference mechanical drawing with the electrical/control drawing to
  confirm conduit runs, sensor locations, and access panels don't conflict
  with structural elements
- Note foundation/anchor bolt pattern and load requirements per equipment
  datasheet

## 2. Foundation & mounting
- Confirm foundation load rating supports equipment weight + dynamic load
  (vibration from motors/conveyors)
- Anchor bolt layout per manufacturer template; verify level before final
  torque
- Vibration isolation (pads/mounts) where specified, particularly near
  rotating equipment

## 3. Equipment installation sequence
1. Position and level base frame using shims as needed
2. Install stationary components (frame, guarding structure) per blueprint
   dimensions
3. Mount rotating equipment (motors, gearboxes, conveyors) per manufacturer
   torque specs
4. Align couplings/shafts (dial indicator or laser alignment method) within
   manufacturer tolerance
5. Install guarding and safety interlocks last, after mechanical
   verification but before electrical energization

## 4. Alignment verification
| Check | Method | Acceptable Tolerance (typical) |
|---|---|---|
| Coupling alignment | Dial indicator / laser alignment | Per coupling manufacturer spec (often <0.005") |
| Level | Precision level | <0.5 mm/m |
| Belt/chain tension | Tension gauge | Per manufacturer spec |
| Anchor bolt torque | Torque wrench | Per bolt grade specification |

## 5. Handoff to controls/electrical
Once mechanically verified and aligned, station is handed off for
electrical/control commissioning (see `technical-specification.md` and
`grafcet-sequence-logic.md`) — mechanical installation must be fully
verified before energizing to avoid damage from misalignment under load.

## Why this matters for a Millwright role
This sequence — blueprint reading, foundation/mounting, precise alignment,
staged handoff to controls — mirrors exactly what's expected when installing
stationary industrial machinery: "Install, align, dismantle and move
stationary industrial machinery... according to layout plans."
